{"parse":{"title":"Brooke Amendment","pageid":53954608,"revid":813233983,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:HUDact69-cover.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/HUDact69-cover.png/220px-HUDact69-cover.png\" width=\"220\" height=\"345\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/HUDact69-cover.png/330px-HUDact69-cover.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/HUDact69-cover.png/440px-HUDact69-cover.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"718\" data-file-height=\"1127\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:HUDact69-cover.png\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Cover of the Housing and Urban Development Act of 1969</div></div></div>\n<p>\u201c<b>Brooke Amendment</b>\u201d is the common name for section 213 (a) of the Housing and Urban Development Act of 1969 (Public Law 91-152) that was sponsored by Senator <a href=\"/wiki/Edward_Brooke_III\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Edward Brooke III\">Edward Brooke III</a> (R-MA), which capped rent in <a href=\"/wiki/Public_housing\" title=\"Public housing\">public housing</a> projects at 25% of tenant\u2019s income.  It amended section 2(1), paragraph two, of the US <a href=\"/wiki/Housing_Act_of_1937\" title=\"Housing Act of 1937\">Housing Act of 1937</a>, and was enacted on <a href=\"/wiki/Christmas_Eve\" title=\"Christmas Eve\">Christmas Eve</a>, 24 December 1969.<sup id=\"cite_ref-HUD_Act_69_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HUD_Act_69-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-HUD.gov_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HUD.gov-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  The Brooke Amendment became the first instance of the benchmark to measure housing affordability, which became known as the \"30 percent rule of thumb\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>  in 1981 when the 25 percent cap was raised to 30 percent of tenant income.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Senator Brooke advocated for two other subsections that were enacted in the Housing and Urban Development Act of 1969.  Section 213 (b) gives the Secretary of <a href=\"/wiki/Housing_and_Urban_Development\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Housing and Urban Development\">Housing and Urban Development</a> (HUD) authority to revoke the 25 percent cap if it results in a reduction of total welfare assistance.  Section 213 (c) amends section 14 of the <a href=\"/wiki/Housing_Act_of_1937\" title=\"Housing Act of 1937\">Housing Act of 1937</a> to ensure the \"low-rent character of public housing projects\" by fixing annual contract contributions according to the current Federal rate of interest.<sup id=\"cite_ref-HUD_Act_69_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HUD_Act_69-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  Together, the three subsections can be referred to as the \"Brooke Amendments\",<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> although the pluralized term is less common.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Brooke_Amendment&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-HUD_Act_69-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-HUD_Act_69_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-HUD_Act_69_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.a0000107235;view=1up;seq=4\">\"Housing and urban development act of 1969 ;Public law 91-152 and section-by-section summary\"</a>. <i>Hathi Trust</i>. Washington&#160;:. 1 January 1969<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">3 May</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Hathi+Trust&amp;rft.atitle=Housing+and+urban+development+act+of+1969+%3BPublic+law+91-152+and+section-by-section+summary.&amp;rft.date=1969-01-01&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbabel.hathitrust.org%2Fcgi%2Fpt%3Fid%3Duc1.a0000107235%3Bview%3D1up%3Bseq%3D4&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABrooke+Amendment\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-HUD.gov-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-HUD.gov_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://portal.hud.gov/hudportal/documents/huddoc?id=Legs_Chron_June2014.pdf\">\"Major Legislation on Housing and Urban Development Enacted Since 1932\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. <i>Housing and Urban Development</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">3 May</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Housing+and+Urban+Development&amp;rft.atitle=Major+Legislation+on+Housing+and+Urban+Development+Enacted+Since+1932&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fportal.hud.gov%2Fhudportal%2Fdocuments%2Fhuddoc%3Fid%3DLegs_Chron_June2014.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABrooke+Amendment\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b>